    <bioghist encodinganalog="5451_">
      <!--Use encodinganalog 5450_ for biog. or 5451_ for historical note, or use a <head> element-->
      <head>Historical Note</head>
      <p>The Missoula office of the U.S. Weather Bureau was established on
		  November 1, 1935, in the Montana Building at 101 Broadway. On November 1, 1938,
		  the office moved one block to the Federal Building. From July 1, 1939, to
		  October 1, 1941, weather observations were also recorded by Civil Aeronautics
		  Administration personnel at Hale Field; this station moved to the Missoula
		  County Airport effective October 1, 1941. The two weather stations were
		  consolidated when the Weather Bureau office moved to the Missoula County
		  Airport on December 1, 1944.</p>
      <p>The Weather Bureau was established in 1870. It was under the authority
		  of the Army Signal Service/Signal Corps until 1891, when it was transferred to
		  the U.S. Department of Agriculture. In 1940 the Weather Bureau was transferred
		  to the U.S. Department of Commerce.</p>
      <p>In Missoula, before establishment of the Weather Bureau office,
		  weather observations were made by the U.S. Army at Fort Missoula from April
		  1893 to May 1898. From May 1898 to November 1935, weather observations were
		  made by University of Montana Professor Morton J. Elrod and his students at his
		  home on West Fifth Street South in Missoula.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The collection contains daily meteorological observations from
		  November 1935 to December 1988. Records from 1973 to 1975 are missing.
		  Materials consist of Weather Bureau forms in bound volumes (1935-1978 and
		  1983-1988) and boxes (1945-1948 and 1979-1982), arranged chronologically. The
		  meteorological observations include data such as temperature, barometric
		  pressure, dewpoint, humidity, wind, precipitation, cloud type, visibility, and
		  general weather conditions. The forms include notes on equipment maintenance
		  and physical description of the various weather station locations.</p>
      <p>WB Form 1001 (later 733j) includes daily records and a monthly
		  summary. Form 1002 is an annual summary. Form 1014 is a daily local record,
		  with index. Form 1130 (later WBAN 10) records airway weather observations.
		  Pilot Reports (abbreviated PIREPS) are monthly reports on weather more than 1.5
		  miles from any airport runway. These reports appear from April 1950 to November
		  1962 but are not clearly titled as a separate form until 1959. Form 450-10
		  (later WS Form H-10) is a monthly equipment operation log. Many volumes include
		  Weather Bureau instructions for preparing the forms, a typed narrative summary
		  of the month's weather, and typed instructions for preparing the daily local
		  record index. Volumes from 1949 on include Forms 1001 and 1130 only; Forms
		  1002, 1014, and indexes no longer appear. Equipment operation logs appear from
		  1968 to 1982. Descriptions of the weather station locations and instrumentation
		  appear on various forms throughout the collection.</p>
      <p>Volumes 8, 10, 12, 14, 15, and 16 include both airport and city office
		  observations, reflecting the two observation stations that were operating from
		  1939 to 1944. Corrections are occasionally noted for a previous month.</p>
    </scopecontent>
